1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,440
 - Hello, and welcome to our lecture on AJAX and JSON.

2
00:00:02,440 --> 00:00:04,280
 I'm Dr. Earl Severance, and I'm your professor,

3
00:00:04,280 --> 00:00:07,040
 and I just wanna, I got a nice Father's Day gift

4
00:00:07,040 --> 00:00:10,920
 from my daughter, and so I'm, to thank her,

5
00:00:10,920 --> 00:00:13,320
 I'm wearing it for this particular lecture.

6
00:00:13,320 --> 00:00:17,160
 So, we have been doing a whole bunch of stuff

7
00:00:17,160 --> 00:00:19,120
 with the request-response cycle, right?

8
00:00:19,120 --> 00:00:23,120
 We go in the server, we run through URLs,

9
00:00:23,120 --> 00:00:27,320
 we enter views, we write templates, we send HTML back,

10
00:00:27,320 --> 00:00:30,040
 and the browser parses that response

11
00:00:30,040 --> 00:00:33,200
 and puts it in the document object model,

12
00:00:33,200 --> 00:00:35,800
 and then most of what we've done has been just sort of fiddling

13
00:00:35,800 --> 00:00:38,000
 with the document object model with JavaScript,

14
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:41,640
 but now we're going to take another important step,

15
00:00:41,640 --> 00:00:44,200
 and that is, we're going to do things

16
00:00:44,200 --> 00:00:45,640
 in the document object model,

17
00:00:45,640 --> 00:00:47,600
 and to the document object model,

18
00:00:47,600 --> 00:00:51,640
 where the JavaScript itself is going to make requests

19
00:00:51,640 --> 00:00:54,520
 to our server code, gonna run through the views,

20
00:00:54,520 --> 00:00:57,400
 run through the URLs, and send data back.

21
00:00:57,400 --> 00:01:00,080
 So the difference is, we're not just sending markup back,

22
00:01:00,080 --> 00:01:02,080
 HTML is our markup format,

23
00:01:02,080 --> 00:01:06,880
 and JSON is our data format.

24
00:01:06,880 --> 00:01:09,600
 So, the web is pretty old now.

25
00:01:09,600 --> 00:01:14,600
 We started on 2003, and the request-response cycle

26
00:01:14,600 --> 00:01:17,320
 was pretty cool, and lots of software,

27
00:01:17,320 --> 00:01:20,760
 lots of libraries, lots of languages knew how

28
00:01:20,760 --> 00:01:24,120
 to talk back and forth across the internet and get data,

29
00:01:24,120 --> 00:01:27,760
 and the question was, is why don't we get something

30
00:01:27,760 --> 00:01:31,200
 other than HTML, and then the argument became,

31
00:01:31,200 --> 00:01:33,760
 what was the syntax that we should use?

32
00:01:33,760 --> 00:01:36,240
 And you can look at my shirt here, somewhere here,

33
00:01:36,240 --> 00:01:38,880
 right there's my shirt, you got some curly braces,

34
00:01:38,880 --> 00:01:40,560
 and then you got some slashes,

35
00:01:40,560 --> 00:01:43,240
 and that actually turned out to be the argument.

36
00:01:43,240 --> 00:01:47,360
 The argument was, whether or not you would use XML, right?

37
00:01:47,360 --> 00:01:49,320
 Whether you use XML or curly braces.

38
00:01:49,320 --> 00:01:51,960
 Now, XML was the first thing,

39
00:01:51,960 --> 00:01:56,000
 and if we hear the word Ajax, that x stands for XML,

40
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,960
 but most of the time we are not sending XML back and forth,

41
00:01:59,960 --> 00:02:02,600
 we're sending JSON back and forth.

42
00:02:02,600 --> 00:02:06,440
 So the idea of moving data across the network,

43
00:02:06,440 --> 00:02:09,680
 we had to agree on what's called a wire format,

44
00:02:09,680 --> 00:02:11,960
 or you could think of it as the network,

45
00:02:11,960 --> 00:02:14,600
 as if we're watching it on a wire and it's going by,

46
00:02:14,600 --> 00:02:16,080
 what would we actually send?

47
00:02:16,080 --> 00:02:18,800
 'Cause in PHP we have arrays,

48
00:02:18,800 --> 00:02:20,000
 in Python we have dictionaries,

49
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:22,400
 in JavaScript we have objects, and Java has things

50
00:02:22,400 --> 00:02:24,760
 like hash maps and array lists.

51
00:02:24,760 --> 00:02:27,080
 And the question is, what are we gonna send back and forth?

52
00:02:27,080 --> 00:02:29,920
 We gotta agree on it, so that we can write something

53
00:02:29,920 --> 00:02:31,520
 in Python and read it in JavaScript,

54
00:02:31,520 --> 00:02:33,480
 and similarly write it in PHP,

55
00:02:33,480 --> 00:02:34,600
 and then read it in JavaScript.

56
00:02:34,600 --> 00:02:37,840
 So we have to agree on a wire format.

57
00:02:37,840 --> 00:02:40,760
 And XML is one of the wire formats,

58
00:02:40,760 --> 00:02:41,680
 we're not gonna talk about it,

59
00:02:41,680 --> 00:02:45,000
 'cause that argument is kinda over.

60
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:48,400
 XML is not bad for documents at rest,

61
00:02:48,400 --> 00:02:51,400
 but it's not a real good wire format.

62
00:02:51,400 --> 00:02:54,240
 So we'll just pretend that JSON is the wire format,

63
00:02:54,240 --> 00:02:57,000
 even though it is a wire format.

64
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:00,560
 The idea is, is that we have to take a structure

65
00:03:00,560 --> 00:03:04,000
 that's inside a server, and we have to serialize it,

66
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:05,800
 which means convert it to a string.

67
00:03:05,800 --> 00:03:07,080
 So it's a Python dictionary,

68
00:03:07,080 --> 00:03:10,200
 which is object-oriented mechanisms

69
00:03:10,200 --> 00:03:11,600
 that make all this stuff work.

70
00:03:11,600 --> 00:03:15,240
 And then we have to say, oh, let's turn this into a string,

71
00:03:15,240 --> 00:03:17,440
 'cause we have to send characters across the internet,

72
00:03:17,440 --> 00:03:19,360
 and then when we receive it on the far end,

73
00:03:19,360 --> 00:03:20,800
 we do what's called deserialize.

74
00:03:20,800 --> 00:03:23,200
 And the word serial means that we're sending it

75
00:03:23,200 --> 00:03:24,480
 kinda one character at a time,

76
00:03:24,480 --> 00:03:26,840
 back in the old days when we used modems,

77
00:03:26,840 --> 00:03:28,960
 and leased lines, and things like that.

78
00:03:28,960 --> 00:03:31,980
 Though see my internet history for some of that.

79
00:03:31,980 --> 00:03:34,520
 So we deserialize it, and it becomes sort of an object

80
00:03:34,520 --> 00:03:36,040
 in JavaScript, in this case,

81
00:03:36,040 --> 00:03:37,640
 if we're going from Python to JavaScript.

82
00:03:37,640 --> 00:03:40,000
 But the idea is that the wire format

83
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:42,100
 is something we agree on,

84
00:03:42,100 --> 00:03:44,540
 and so it doesn't matter what language we're dealing with,

85
00:03:44,540 --> 00:03:46,400
 the wire format is something each language

86
00:03:46,400 --> 00:03:48,280
 has to be able to serialize to send,

87
00:03:48,280 --> 00:03:51,360
 and deserialize to receive.

88
00:03:51,360 --> 00:03:53,880
 So I have a video, an interview that I did a long time ago,

89
00:03:53,880 --> 00:03:55,520
 with a fellow named Douglas Cockford,

90
00:03:55,520 --> 00:03:58,720
 he does not claim he's the inventor of JSON,

91
00:03:58,720 --> 00:04:00,480
 he's just the person who said,

92
00:04:00,480 --> 00:04:04,080
 wow, this is a really cool format, and let's write it down.

93
00:04:04,080 --> 00:04:07,960
 And it's really nothing more than a slight adjustment

94
00:04:07,960 --> 00:04:11,240
 to the object literal notation, meaning the constant,

95
00:04:11,240 --> 00:04:13,680
 what a constant is in JavaScript

96
00:04:13,680 --> 00:04:15,880
 when you wanna just assign a constant.

97
00:04:15,880 --> 00:04:18,420
 So we say x equals two, two's that constant,

98
00:04:18,420 --> 00:04:21,920
 but you can also say x equals curly brace something.

99
00:04:21,920 --> 00:04:26,140
 And so he's like, well, why don't we just use this?

100
00:04:26,140 --> 00:04:30,160
 And he called it JSON, and he registered JSON.org,

101
00:04:30,160 --> 00:04:33,840
 and it just turns out, I really wish I knew

102
00:04:33,840 --> 00:04:38,840
 the extent to which imitating the Python dictionary syntax

103
00:04:38,840 --> 00:04:40,560
 was part of the goal.

104
00:04:40,560 --> 00:04:42,380
 In some ways, it's almost more similar

105
00:04:42,380 --> 00:04:44,440
 to the Python dictionary syntax

106
00:04:44,440 --> 00:04:47,040
 when you're doing key value pairs,

107
00:04:47,040 --> 00:04:49,440
 when the keys are strings in Python dictionary.

108
00:04:49,440 --> 00:04:54,440
 So this is some legitimate JavaScript code.

109
00:04:54,440 --> 00:04:55,900
 This is a constant.

110
00:04:55,900 --> 00:04:58,300
 I could say who equals X or I could see

111
00:04:58,300 --> 00:05:01,260
 who equals open curly brace, name colon Chuck,

112
00:05:01,260 --> 00:05:03,780
 age colon 29, college colon true, you know,

113
00:05:03,780 --> 00:05:06,420
 strings, integers, Booleans, you can have lists

114
00:05:06,420 --> 00:05:08,100
 and you can have objects within objects

115
00:05:08,100 --> 00:05:10,940
 and lists within objects and blah, blah, blah, blah, blah,

116
00:05:10,940 --> 00:05:13,100
 so it's a pretty simple syntax.

117
00:05:13,100 --> 00:05:16,860
 I mean, part of the thing that Crockford argues

118
00:05:16,860 --> 00:05:20,160
 is that it's just a syntax that any developer,

119
00:05:20,160 --> 00:05:22,900
 if left alone long enough, would just invent it

120
00:05:22,900 --> 00:05:24,040
 and I have to agree with that.

121
00:05:24,040 --> 00:05:26,220
 I have to say that this syntax,

122
00:05:26,220 --> 00:05:29,260
 I can't say, whoa, I don't like this.

123
00:05:29,260 --> 00:05:31,580
 I wish I could improve on it somehow.

124
00:05:31,580 --> 00:05:34,660
 So the JSON syntax is a,

125
00:05:34,660 --> 00:05:37,440
 it's not exactly the same as a JavaScript syntax.

126
00:05:37,440 --> 00:05:39,260
 It's kind of like, let's keep it simple

127
00:05:39,260 --> 00:05:43,420
 and have a subset of the JavaScript object literal syntax.

128
00:05:43,420 --> 00:05:47,660
 And so I've got some sample code that you can go play with

129
00:05:47,660 --> 00:05:50,260
 and all it does is it says who equals open curly brace,

130
00:05:50,260 --> 00:05:51,860
 blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, exactly the code

131
00:05:51,860 --> 00:05:53,820
 I showed you before and console.log it.

132
00:05:53,820 --> 00:05:55,020
 That's all it does.

133
00:05:55,020 --> 00:05:55,860
 It doesn't print it.

134
00:05:55,860 --> 00:05:57,100
 It doesn't send it across the network.

135
00:05:57,100 --> 00:05:58,020
 It doesn't do anything.

136
00:05:58,020 --> 00:06:00,680
 It just console.logs it and you see that

137
00:06:00,680 --> 00:06:04,580
 that is the way we define a constant object.

138
00:06:04,580 --> 00:06:06,760
 An object is a constant and so,

139
00:06:08,580 --> 00:06:09,860
 but that's not so interesting.

140
00:06:09,860 --> 00:06:13,700
 What is more interesting is when we can produce code

141
00:06:13,700 --> 00:06:16,500
 inside of the server in say Python

142
00:06:16,500 --> 00:06:18,580
 and then send it to a browser.

143
00:06:18,580 --> 00:06:20,780
 So here we have a very simple view

144
00:06:20,780 --> 00:06:24,020
 and the sample code is up there on djfree.com

145
00:06:24,020 --> 00:06:25,380
 for you to look at

146
00:06:25,380 --> 00:06:29,900
 and we are going to have a JSON fun path.

147
00:06:29,900 --> 00:06:34,460
 This is gonna be a function style view.

148
00:06:34,460 --> 00:06:36,820
 Time sleep is just so that when you play with a sample,

149
00:06:36,820 --> 00:06:39,980
 you can kind of pause this for just a moment.

150
00:06:39,980 --> 00:06:41,220
 Normally you wouldn't pause.

151
00:06:41,220 --> 00:06:43,360
 So we just construct a dictionary.

152
00:06:43,360 --> 00:06:46,540
 That's a Python dictionary and again, wow,

153
00:06:46,540 --> 00:06:48,300
 it looks a lot like a JavaScript object

154
00:06:48,300 --> 00:06:50,260
 but if you do it in PHP, it looks quite different

155
00:06:50,260 --> 00:06:52,140
 or if you do it in Java, it looks quite different

156
00:06:52,140 --> 00:06:54,220
 but it turns out in Python and JavaScript,

157
00:06:54,220 --> 00:06:55,340
 they're very similar

158
00:06:55,340 --> 00:06:58,340
 and then we're returning JSON response

159
00:06:58,340 --> 00:06:59,860
 and then handing that dictionary.

160
00:06:59,860 --> 00:07:04,860
 Now, normally when we have a normal HTML page,

161
00:07:05,200 --> 00:07:08,300
 we're sending back an HTTP response

162
00:07:08,300 --> 00:07:09,520
 and we're sending a string back

163
00:07:09,520 --> 00:07:11,420
 but this time we're sending a JSON response

164
00:07:11,420 --> 00:07:13,200
 and we're sending an object back.

165
00:07:13,200 --> 00:07:16,020
 Django sees JSON response and says,

166
00:07:16,020 --> 00:07:17,620
 I'm gonna set the headers the right way,

167
00:07:17,620 --> 00:07:18,780
 I'm gonna serialize this

168
00:07:18,780 --> 00:07:21,020
 and I'm gonna send this thing out as a string.

169
00:07:21,020 --> 00:07:26,140
 And so if you go to this endpoint, JSON fun,

170
00:07:26,140 --> 00:07:27,980
 and you look at it in raw data,

171
00:07:27,980 --> 00:07:30,740
 you see that it's been compressed into a string.

172
00:07:30,740 --> 00:07:34,220
 That's really curly brace and double quote, yada yada.

173
00:07:34,220 --> 00:07:38,500
 Now you also see your browser sometimes shows it parsed,

174
00:07:38,500 --> 00:07:40,940
 meaning it's showing it after parsing.

175
00:07:40,940 --> 00:07:43,260
 So you can see the raw data before parsing

176
00:07:43,260 --> 00:07:46,900
 and then you can actually see the JSON data after parsing.

177
00:07:46,900 --> 00:07:48,580
 It's kind of the same thing,

178
00:07:48,580 --> 00:07:52,620
 it's just one's a string and one is an object.

179
00:07:52,620 --> 00:07:56,160
 And part and parcel of moving JSON back and forth

180
00:07:56,160 --> 00:07:58,380
 to the browser is you got things like the content type

181
00:07:58,380 --> 00:08:02,860
 which is application slash JSON rather than text slash HTML.

182
00:08:02,860 --> 00:08:06,340
 And then there's other things like content size,

183
00:08:06,340 --> 00:08:08,040
 et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

184
00:08:08,040 --> 00:08:12,140
 So that's about all there is to JSON.

185
00:08:12,140 --> 00:08:14,000
 It's so simple, it's so elegant.

186
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:17,420
 So up next, we're gonna talk about doing a chat app

187
00:08:17,420 --> 00:08:19,920
 which really brings together a lot of this JavaScript,

188
00:08:19,920 --> 00:08:23,360
 JavaScript objects, JavaScript in the browser and JSON.

189
00:08:23,360 --> 00:08:25,940
 (upbeat music)

190
00:08:32,860 --> 00:08:34,920
 you

